Exploring the city of skyscrapers  Hong Kong is a modern metropolis filled with towering buildings that reach for the skies. location.city_name: 麥文記麵家 Mak Man Kee Noodle Shop

social_posts.post_text: 🇭🇰Bringing back memories with every bite! Mak Man Kee Noodle Shop, 麥文記! My parents' go-to spot for dates in their student days, Mak Man Kee Noodle Shop in Hong Kong serves up the best wonton noodles. 60 years strong and still as delicious as ever, with silky noodles in a clear broth and perfectly sized wontons filled with juicy shrimp. And don't forget to add a small side dish of chives 韭菜花 +蠔油! Every visit to Mak Man Kee Noodle Shop feels like a trip home, and it wouldn't be complete without a stop at the nearby Australian Dairy Company 澳牛 afterwards.  #MakManKeeNoodleShop #hongkongeats #wontonnoodles 🍜🤤 #foodieheaven 🌟

social_posts.post_text:
If you're ever in Hong Kong, you must try the local cafe 茶餐廳 ☕️favorite 🥛 澳州牛奶公司 - Australian Dairy Company! This authentic Hong Kong-style cafe is known for its silky smooth steamed milk and egg custard 蛋白炖鲜奶 & must-try scrambled eggs on toast 宇宙級炒蛋多士. 🍞
If you have room for more, I highly recommend the ham macaroni🍝, char siu soup noodles, etc. The food here is consistently delicious, and the service is notoriously blunt - but hey, it's all part of the experience!
Just come prepared to order quickly and share tables. And if you're a fan of scrambled eggs, you won't find a better version anywhere else! With @kurakura0928 
.

location.city_name: 妹記生滾粥品  Mui Kee Congee - Hong Kong

social_posts.post_text:
妹記生滾粥品, Mui Kee Congee, located in an upper-level food court in Mong Kok,
is renowned for its traditional copper pot Cantonese congee with fresh grass carp fish.

What made a great congee? The ingredients used must be fresh and the texture must be silky smooth. To achieve this, the congee must be cooked quickly so that it is hot enough to cook the ingredients just enough to release their flavors, and then immediately taken off the heat. Each ingredient has a different cooking time, so it requires great skill from the chef.
Mui Kee can be said to be the best Cantonese congee in Hong Kong, always maintaining a consistently high standard that can be passed down from generation to generation. It has a strong local flavor and is very satisfying after eating.We ordered: 
魚腩粉腸粥
Fish Belly & intestines Congee
魷魚魚腩粥

One of the hardest-to-book Chinese private kitchen(私房菜) restaurants in Hong Kong . Have you been there before? On a rainy night, we enjoyed a delicious feast at this hidden gem. Renowned chef Vicky reinvents Cantonese cuisine and has won Asia's 50 Best Restaurants and a spot on the World's 50 Best Restaurants list.

the chef's set menu and were first served a warm eight-treasure tea and a snack of spicy cashews to stave off the winter chill. For starters, we had steamed abalone with Yunnan pepper and sea mushroom, smoked eggplant with sour sauce, spicy oysters with century egg, and drunken South African abalone. The soup was almond milk with egg white and mountain yam.

The main dishes included steamed Threadfin with preserved mustard greens, steamed emperor crab claw with minced garlic and rice rolls, smoked pigeon with sugarcane juice, sour soup winter melon pot, and abalone sauce with matsutake mushroom and fish maw with rice. For dessert, we had osmanthus jelly with coconut snowflakes, followed by seasonal fruits.😋

☕️Have you ever tried Bestow & The Tabibito, @bestowcoffee a Japanese dessert and coffee shop in the bustling streets of Mong Kok? Tucked away on a side street in the middle of the chaos of street food vendors, this cozy spot presents a uniquely Japanese aesthetic with a selection of curated goods available for purchase. 
The cafe is divided into two areas - Bestow, which serves delicious seasonal sweets and savory dishes, and The Tabibito, which features curated goods for sale. The minimal plain white and wood interior creates a spacious and comfortable atmosphere, making it the perfect place to enjoy a cup of coffee or tea. Their hand-drip coffee is a must-try, and their presentation of food and drink on handmade Japanese ceramics is simply exquisite, perfect for photos.
.

Have you been to @bar.coucou yet? It's located in Venice Beach, just a few steps away from the ocean. Coucou is a restaurant that focuses on artisanal cocktails alongside delicious dishes. Its name comes from the French word for "hello," which is a more intimate greeting. 
Inspired by the bar and tavern culture of France, Coucou blends traditional French cuisine with California coastal ingredients, resulting in a sophisticated menu.
If you happen to be in the area, it's worth a visit.
It's a great place to have a drink with a couple of friends.
.

🤤Craving authentic Korean cold noodles 🍜and delicious beef bone soup? Lee Ga, a gem in Koreatown, has got you covered. I‘ve been here several times this summer to savor some tasty cold noodles.🧊
.
Their buckwheat cold noodles are a must-try, with a chewy texture and a spicy kick that sets them apart. Pair them with eggs, cucumbers, and pickled radishes for a delightful combination. The non-spicy soup noodles are equally fantastic as well.👌🏻
.
Don’t miss their galbi tang (beef bone soup) and seok galbi (spicy grilled beef ribs soup) either. The meat is tender, and the flavors are spot-on. And for a unique treat, try the grilled meat wrap with the cold noodles—it‘s a match made in heaven!🥩
.
Lastly, their side dishes, including kimchi 🥟dumplings, are a delightful bonus. This place is a favorite among foodies, so be prepared to wait in line. Can’t wait to come back and explore more options. If you have any other recommendations in LA‘s Koreatown, please share!
.
📍Lee Ga 
698 S Vermont Ave Ste 106 
Los Angeles, CA 90005

🍱 Join me at the 'Taste of Japan at Shibumi' event, a prelude to Dine LA Restaurant Week, starting October 6th, 2023. Experience the artistry of Japanese cuisine as Shibumi takes us on a culinary journey through a carefully curated multi-course menu, with a spotlight on the exquisite flavors of scallops and yellowtail. 

This event aims to showcase the beauty of Japanese seafood and raise awareness about the accessibility of authentic Japanese cuisine right here in the States. Don't miss the chance to savor the same delightful menu available during Dine LA Restaurant Week!

Swipe left to discover the culinary maestro behind these delectable creations. Let's come together to celebrate the rich tapestry of flavors at #DineLAShibumi @dinela 
thank you @shibumidtla @chefderekwilcox @chefdavidschlosser

If you don't want to Grill it yourself and still want to eat barbecue skewers, then Fei Xiang Gong is the place for you! 👍🏼 This barbecue skewer restaurant is located in Koreatown and, like Feng Mao, is the OG of Koreatown skewers. The owner is from Yanbian, so it can be considered a mixed style of BBQ skewers. 
. 
When at 5pm we went, the restaurant was still empty, but before we knew it, the whole place was filled with people. There was even a constant line outside.
. 
Their skewers come in sets of five and it's great for group gatherings. Most of the skewers don't have much flavor on their own, so you need to dip them in the housemade sauces. The skewer grills are self-service and self-rotate, which is great for lazy people and beginners like me💯.
. 
Fei Xiang Gong not only has skewers but also cold dishes, hot dishes, soups, and main dishes. The variety is extensive! We ordered lamb soup, which is heavy in flavor and has a lot of meat—a generous portion.
. 
📍Fei Xiang Gong
356 S Western Ave Ste 203
Los Angeles, CA 90020
